= Personal Statement: Please describe pivotal experiences, opportunities, and/or challenges (including any financial or access to education barriers) that have influenced your educational and professional development. (250 words max)

One of the biggest challenges during my undergraduate years was managing a substantial course load alongside research commitments. Despite graduating in two years because of financial pressure, I was able to balance research opportunities and participation in clubs alongside schoolwork. Within that time, I was able to do research in both HCI and theory, founded and led an Algorithms Club and participated in competitive programming. Though demanding, this experience was deeply rewarding and prepared me to handle the challenges of graduate research.

Taking an active interest in research became the most transformative part of my undergraduate experience. Being on campus gave me opportunities to attend talks, meet other research students, and most importantly, to work with postdocs, PhD students, other undergraduates, and professors across various research areas. Despite being relatively new to research, working with others exposed me to new perspectives on how their papers related to other work, and helped me better understand where my project fit within the broader literature. This has been true for both HCI and algorithms; for instance, taking combinatorial optimization helped me situate my fair division survey within the broader optimization literature and understand connections between seemingly diverse problems. These experiences inspired me to pursue a career in research, and to pursue a PhD in Theoritical Computer Science. 
